result.name: Brooklyn We Go Hard: The Biggie Smalls Tour
result.description:
Christopher Wallace aka the Notorious B.I.G. aka Biggie Smalls is synonomous with Brooklyn.This cross-Brooklyn stomp that visits many of the hotspots where Biggie Smalls learned to craft his remarkable freestyle rap and rhymes. 

Sites include George Westinghouse HS, which is where Christopher Wallace went to school along with Busta Rhymes and Jay-Z. Across the street from Westinghouse is Albee Square, where Biggie rapped about Albee as well as lots of other rappers name-check it in their songs, including Lil Kim. Then it’s over to Juniors, with their world-famous cheesecake, which is undoubtedly one of the hotspots where Biggie earned his nickname. That’s a signed photo him with Jay-Z on the wall.
Farther along in Fort Greene is Habana Outpost, featuring an enormous, posthumous Comandante Biggie! mural, painted by legendary graffiti and street artist Lee Quinones. There’s Brooklyn’s Queen of All Saints School, the Country House Diner, which was a local favorite of Biggie’s, The Golden Krust Jamaican patty bakery, the DLC Comprehensive Medical Center, formerly the Mayfair Grocery and other famous locations where Biggie hustled.
result.title: Follow Brooklyn through the life and times of the Notorious B.I.G.

result.name: Pursuit of Freedom Walking Tour
result.description:
Free African Americans — lived in downtown Brooklyn from 1810 onwards. They built institutions to combat racism on behalf of all people of color, especially when the end of slavery in New York State in 1827 came without equality. The financial panic of 1837 halted Brooklyn’s rapid urban transformation. One year later, free black New Yorkers took advantage of low property prices to intentionally establish the community of Weeksville as a self-sufficient haven for African Americans. Located in Brooklyn’s ninth ward, Weeksville was the most distant and secluded anti-slavery base from the city’s downtown area, thus it offered safety, refuge, and freedom to its residents.

The Weeksville Heritage center continues to be a bastion for the black cultural experience in Brooklyn. Regularly hostings exhibitions and it’s permanent collection, it is a forward thinking archival and living center for our history, this tour ends with a tour of the grounds.
result.title: Explore the anti-slavery movement and black prosperity in Brooklyn.

result.name: A Voyage Through Gullah Cuisine
result.description:
Join Chef Pamela D. Jones on a lesson in African American heritage and history over food. You'll be treated to a four course traditional gullah meal complete with tips and tricks to making the dishes on your own.  

Here's the menu:
Appetizer #1: Boiled Peanuts 
Salted boiled peanuts were named the Official Snack of South Carolina. Our family grew peanuts on our farm when I was a child. It was so interesting to see how they were harvested from the ground and dried out on a bed spread in one of my grandmother’s bedrooms and then boiled in large batches and given to neighbors as gifts! 

Appetizer #2: Frogmore Stew (aka Low Country Boil) Although there are many versions of this dish around, the name Frogmore Stew was coined in the 1960s by Richard Gay, one of the owners of Gay Fish Company, circa 1948, on St. Helena Island. It has sausage, shrimp, potatoes and corn for an all-in-one pot all-you-can-eat buffet!" 
**Vegetarian option is available - succotash: tomatoes, lima beans, okra and corn 

Entree : Fried Catfish, Red rice with smoked sausage, Collards Greens, Cornbread & Pot Liquor
Red Rice and Sausage is a staple in the Southern United States, especially in the coastal areas of Charleston, SC, and Savannah, Ga.. In Charleston, red rice and sausage is a way of life. It’s eaten with many different types of meals, but especially seafood. * 
*Vegetarian Option is available, no sausage** 

One of the ways that the slaves made the most out of the vegetable scraps that were given to them was to drink what is called the “ pot likker ” or “ pot liquor ”, i.e., the water that’s leftover in the pot after the collards are cooked, a slight greenish hue. Pot Liquor is traditionally eaten with cornbread. **Vegetarian Option is available - collard greens and/or roasted cabbage** 
Homemade Cornbread is a perfect accompaniment for collards greens and pot liquor. 

Dessert : Blackberry Dumplings 
This recipe for Blackberries and Dumplings has been one of my favorites since childhood. I can remember my Mama making blackberries and dumplings with wild blackberries we picked from the field. 

Condiments : Homemade Tartar Sauce - for catfish, Southern Chow Chow - for anything you want Honey Butter - for cornbread, Texas Pete Hot Sauce - for fish
result.title: A Taste of Gullah Cuisine in ATL

Alexandra Township (known as Alex, or Gomora) is the oldest township in South Africa and a bustling part of Johannesburg. In-between Alex's bustling marketplaces and working communities, there are reminders everywhere of the township's storied history, struggles, progress and influence in South African art, culture and politics.

You'll take tours of the Heritage Museum, Nelson Mandela's first Johannesburg house, and Kings Theatre - learning everything you need to know about the stories that built Alex.

You'll also have breakfast with commuters; lunch with a local family; and drinks and music at a township tavern - experiencing a true day in the life of an Alex Johannesburger.

result.name: Remembrance at the African Burial Ground
result.description:
In 1991, the remains of 15,000 free and enslaved Africans was discovered in lower Manhattan.  The discovery altered the conversation around slavery in NY - learn how and join an important year of return ceremony.

You'll get a private tour of the African Burial Ground led by a senior curator. You'll get a chance to learn the history behind the excavation, the impact of the discovery, and the history of enslaved Africans and their contributions to the development of New York City.

After your tour you'll have the chance to participate in a traditional African libations ceremony in an effort to memorialize your experience and connect to those who were here.
result.title: The remains of 15,000 free and enslaved Africans was discovered in lower Manhattan. Honor their legacy.

result.name: Beyond Dreads Rastafari Culture in Brooklyn
result.description:
Rasta’s are eponymous with roots, reggae, and pan-africanism. 

“From Morris Heights in the Bronx to Jamaica and Hillside in Queens, and from 125th Street in Harlem and Washington Square Park in Manhattan to Crown Heights and Bedford-Stuyvesant in Brooklyn, the sights and ‘word sounds’ of Rastafari levity have become an indelible part of the fabric of life in New York City.” – Randal L. Hepner

Rastafari is the most successful social movement ever to emerge from the Caribbean. The United States and New York, in particular, were and remain among the most important scenes of Rastafari activity. Growth of the Rastafari movement emerged after the waves of Caribbean migration, particularly since 1960s and 1970s. There are many Jamaicans in parts of Brooklyn, like Flatbush or Crown Heights, often called “Little Jamaica”. In 1990 Flatbush was recognized as “New York’s most West Indian neighborhood” and a center of Caribbean tradition, culture, and activities, of which Rastafari is probably the most famous and appealing.

This experience takes you inside Rasta culture with an emphasis on food and healing traditions. You’ll be guided with our expert guide, a flatbush resident and devotee of Rastafarianism.
result.title: Step into Flatbush to discover a taste of ital.
result.todo: Expert Guide, 3 Beverages, Two Food Tastings, Healing Herbs Tutorial, Blessing

result.name: Day Trip To The Champagne Region
result.description:
The day starts when your host and chauffeur meet you at your hotel to ride to Champagne. During the ride, you’ll get a crash course in Champagne to get you started on your bubbly adventure properly!

The first stop is a small town called Chouilly, where we’ll have   Our first tour and tasting is at the brand new state-of-the-art facility of Champagne Nicolas Feuillatte. This facility really shows you how you make Champagne in the 21st century.

Back in the car, we’ll drive down the most expensive street in the world, the Avenue de Champagne. It received this title due to all the priceless bottles that stretch for miles underground in chalk cellars. You can enjoy free time for lunch on your own in Epernay, or take in another tasting at a smaller champagne house. 

Next is a tasting at a smaller champagne house. This really helps you see the difference between big brands and grower champagnes. Lucky for you, the driver has a big trunk to keep all your champagne bottles safe and sound.

Off to Reims we go for a few pictures of the Cathedral Notre Dame de Reims. Then just around the corner we’ll have a wine and cheese pairing with one of the best fromagers in Reims.

Whew, what a day! But if you aren’t tired yet, we may have a special surprise. With memories of an amazing day of wine tasting and quite possibly with stars still dancing on your palate, our chauffeur will return us back to Paris and ordinary life, happy in the knowledge that you have experienced in this corner of paradise.
result.title: A Day Trip To Paradise With A Champagne Expert

Champagne tasting fees

While much of this is associated with the long line of rappers that hail from this part of the borough, most don't know the history of black wealth that was the root of black migration here. No two places tell this story more than Weeksville, one of America's first free black communities, and Stuyvesant Heights a long time bastion of the black middle class in Brooklyn. This experience will take you on a tour of these neighborhoods through historians, residents, and the architecture that makes them continue to standout today.

result.name: Views and Quads at Lac Rose
result.description:
Less than an hour away from the capital city of Senegal Lac Rose is separated by  narrow dunes from the Atlantic Ocean and, as expected its salt content is very high. Its salinity compares to that of the Dead Sea and it is actually impossible to do anything but float when you enter its waters.

Its distinct pink color is caused by the Dunaliella salina bacteria, which is attracted by the lake’s salt content. The bacteria produces a red pigment in order to absorb the sunlight. The lake isn't always pink unfortunately, you can almost guarantee a pink view during the dry season (which lasts from November to June and less so during the rainy season from July to October. Even when the lake isn't pink this experience includes an epic sand dune ride to a secluded beach, good food, and lots of adventure.
result.title: See the pink lake, in real life!

Touba is the holy city of Mouridism and the burial place of its founder, Shaikh Ahmadou Bàmba Mbàcke who founded Mouridism as a revolutionary pushback against French Cultural Imperialism in Senegal. This experience introduces you to Mouridism, takes you on a tour of this unique, self-governing municipality, and showcases the spiritual practice of this distinct muslim community through the people who live it everyday.

Note: Women must dress modestly and cover their heads to participate in this experience.
result.title: Explore Mouridism and A Cultural Revolution
result.todo: RT Transport from Dakar, Lunch, History Tour, Mosque Visit, Visit with descendants of Amadou Bamba the founder of the Mouride Brotherhood

result.name: Street Art Tour of Medina
result.description: Medina is the cultural heartbeat of Dakar. A number of notable Senegalese people, including the world-famous singer Youssou N'Dour and Omar Pene were born in this neighborhood that sits in the center of the city. On this experience you'll learn the history of this hood through an artist passionate about bringing the galleries to the streets.
result.title: Explore Medina Through Art With A Legend
result.todo: Street Art Tour with an Artist, Dibiterie Visit

experience_reviews.content: I loved this tour! I got to see a rarely-seen side of Dakar (to me, and I've lived here for 2+ years) and we even met Youssou Ndour's dad. The art was great and the neighborhood had great energy. The hosts were very open to all questions and I got great photos.

result.title: Explore the Themes of Islam and Cultural Preservation in Dakar

result.name: Style Noire: A Kantamanto thrift market experience
result.description: Kantamanto is Ghana’s biggest second hand clothes market and it’s right in the heart of the capital, Accra. Kantamanto is home to one of the largest thrift markets in West Africa, annexed to Makola Market; the largest point of trade in the city. Kantamanto is a community on its own – full of arrangements of hand-me-down clothes, vehicle spare parts, home decor and footwear, which together give it the look of a grand flea market with almost no space left to spare. It provides clothes to about 80% of Accra's population. This is where you find vintage clothing . Take a thrifting tour through the Kantamanto market with Afrodistrict who has been thrifting there for 15years. Interact with the locals there and experience Kwamena bargaining power on anything you want to buy.
result.title: Turn second hand finds into the finest style with the experts

He conceptualizes West movie posters and shop signages and artistically constructed coffins. result.name: Nima market street food Crawl
result.description:
When you ask people what their impression of a place is, one of the first things they will talk about is food.I have had some amazing meals in my life but the most memorable food experiences have been from street vendors. There is beauty in street food culture at Nima market which makes exploring the corners of Nima interesting. Nima is the north of the city center and has a lot of migrants from the north of Ghana living and doing their businesses within the community. The most common language spoken is Hausa. 
There is so much inspiration and stories about the market that I’m fascinated about, from vegetable stands to display of luscious aroma of spices.  The beauty and appreciation of food hinges on not just the taste but also on the health benefits of the foods consumed. Nima is a great place to sample the yummiest northern staples made with the freshest ingredients in front of you which makes you more comfortable and the closeness encourages conversation. As a traveller, you want to experience all that you can from the country you find yourself in and connect with the locals.  

Join me !

The graffiti workshop will go down as a true highlight of our time in Ghana, mainly as a result of our boys being able to work with Kingsley who taught them how to spray and allowed them to create their own graffiti artworks on the walls outside his studio. result.name: The Return: Cape Coast Castle Experience
result.description: Cape Coast and Elmina Castles are two of the largest remaining structures symbolizing the last point of contact for millions of Africans who left the continent to be enslaved across the Americas. This experience includes a tour of the castles, a historical walking tour of Cape Coast where the vestiges of the slave trade remain, lunch, and a reflection and naming ceremony for those commemorating their return to the motherland.
result.title: Explore two legendary historic points in the slave trade and commemorate your return with a naming ceremony.
result.todo: Roundtrip Transport from Accra, Entrance to Cape Coast and Elmina Castles, Naming Ceremony, Expert Guide, Oceanfront Lunch, Water
result.meetup_description: You'll meet your driver at Oxford Street Mall right in front of the Shoprite. In the event that you are booked privately - hotel pickup will be arranged.

experience_reviews.content: This experience is hard to explain with words but I will try. We learn so much more than any educational institution I've attended. The feeling you runs through you as you stand in the room that contained slaves that were in trouble and kept there to death is incomparable. This experience stays with you long after you leave. What an experience. It included a drive through the beautiful land, tour guide experience at both castles, naming ceremony, and lunch by the coast. If you visit Accra, you must go!

Sebastian did an excellent service with this experience. He was very engaging, impactful and informative. He is really passionate in his craft and it shows.

I would highly recommend this experience. TasteMakers + Sebastian is a winning combination.

My day tour to Cape Coast and Elmina Castles was extremely worthwhile.  I highly recommend it!  Osei was my wonderful driver from Accra to Cape Coast; I was the only passenger and enjoyed our conversation. Then we met Sebastian for the tours. He demonstrated his incredible knowledge of the brutal realities of the slave trade that originated from both castles. My time in Cape Coast concluded with lunch at a beach-front restaurant which was delicious.   Thank you!

An incredible and moving experience, one of the notable highlights of my trip to Ghana that I will never forget. Sebastian was an amazing tour guide and he made my trip to the Cape Coast unforgettable.

Le forts de cape Coast et d’elmina font partie des lieux de mémoire emblématique de la Maafa au Ghana. 
Visite forte en émotions , triste, mais également très instructive grâce à Sebastian .

I am so grateful I was fortunate to have this experience in Cape Coast on my first visit to Ghana! Sebastian was a phenomenal storyteller and tour guide of the Cape Coast and Elmina slave castles, painstakingly detailing the horrors and abominations experienced by my beautiful African people over 400 years ago during the slave trade first started by the Portuguese. Whew! So many horrific details that one does not even begin to think of ordinarily - from the defecation people would have to excrete from their bodies and then subsequently live in to being chained to strangers who do not speak the same language and literally dies side by side. Everyone - Black, White, Latino, Asian - should experience this tour when visiting Ghana to listen to the pain humans inflicted on one another because of greed and selfish intent.

Sebastian was phenomenal. He was informative and entertaining. I was able to get a taste of what the slaves when through and it was a powerful experience that my group and I will never forget. I highly recommend this experience because it is so well executed. I’ve already shared with several friends and followers info on how to book their trip.

result.name: A Ghanaian High Tea and Yoga
result.description:
It's an intimate Yoga session on a rooftop in Accra during sunset. It is also accompanied with Ghanaian tea and health talk. Minimum booking is 2 people

1. We start the experience with High Tea with a Ghanaian twist: locally produced Moringa tea (2 varieties iced tea) and tropical dried fruits. While we sit on cushions and mats, I will give an introduction and overview to myself + my agribusiness + the story of the tea + fruit we are eating and drinking. (30 mins)
2. After a quick bathroom break (if necessary) we'll shift to the Vinyasa yoga part of the session: dynamic flow yoga that is challenging, but accessible for all levels and sizes. (55 mins)
3. After an engaging and vigorous Vinyasa session, we'll close the evening experience with slow, deep, restorative yoga and aromatherapy. (35 mins)
Each session will be accompanied by live music. Each participant will leave with a goodie bag of dried fruit and Moringa tea.

Roosterkoek (bread dough cooked on the fire)

Ribeye steak

From there, take a local taxi to Soweto, where Lelo will show you how to prepare and cook traditional fare. Enjoy with a group of people and get a different feel of Soweto than you normally would.
result.title: JOHANNESBURG
result.meetup: Bree Street Taxi Rank, Johannesburg, South Africa
result.todo: Market Shopping Experience, Transport, Cooking Lesson, 2 Beverages

result.name: Soul Replenishing Art Crawl
result.description: Gallery hopping is a good way to replenish ones soul. Starting off in Rosebank with a plethora of galleries to choose from starting off with a personal favorite Everard Read and work our way throughout the galleries as all the galleries in Rosebank are of close proximity. As we stroll, we'll pop by one of my favorite bistros for a delicious bite as we connect on the pieces we've seen.
result.title: JOHANNESBURG
result.todo: Lunch, Gallery Crawl, Curator Meets

result.name: Meryl's Urban Bootcamp
result.description: Join Meryl in a morning fitness class! Before you get started, talk with Meryl about how she began her fitness bootcamp and then jump into a full body workout session that will get your abs, upper body, and legs toned in no time! All fitness levels from beginner to advanced are welcome. End the experience with some smoothies to wind down. The workouts are structured in a loop style fashion fusing a mixture of body weight, weighted, and functional exercises geared towards improving fitness, full-body muscle tone, torching body fat and of course having a great time while we're at it. The exercises have been designed to fit all levels of ability, there will be harder and easier options for everyone so don’t be put off if this is your first fitness class! Just ensure you bring a bottle of water to keep you hydrated and a towel to wipe off the good sweat.
result.title: JOHANNESBURG
result.todo: Outdoor Fitness Class

result.name: The Joburg Jol
result.description: "Jol" - the local slang for "party" - is exactly what you will get up to with Ntsako. No night is the same as he takes you on a VIP Party Hopping experience around Jozi that depends entirely on what is happening that night. Past stops along the party route have included: whisky tastings, product launches, art exhibition openings, and much more
result.title: JOHANNESBURG
result.todo: Nightlife Entry Fees, VIP Access

experience_reviews.content: Although Ntasko couldn't make it, my husband and I had a blast with Musa!!!! She is a rockstar!!! Great food at Epicure with Chef Coco, Fantastic drinks and dope club scene.

result.name: Vintage Shops and Rooftop Dinner With A Designer
result.description: Explore Joburg's vintage fashion and design history with a rising designer. Kick off the day with a thrifting experience at a local market and shop some preloved clothes, then head to a hidden museum in Auckland park to explore the Victorian/Edwardian interiors. Round off the day with drinks and a set menu of traditional South African dishes on a rooftop in the heart of Johannesburg.
result.title: JOHANNESBURG
result.todo: Thrifting Experience, Rooftop Dinner, Wine Pairings

result.name: From Highlife to Afrobeats: A Musical Exploration
result.description: Palm wine, vintage records, and karaoke - that's just the beginning. Join Sharifah our resident culture vulture on a journey through Accra that focuses on the music that originated here.
result.title: Explore African music from Ghanaian highlife to present day afrobeats with a music lover and cultural curator
result.todo: Vintage Record Hunting, Lunch, Palm Wine Tasting, Afrobeats Party
result.meetup_description: The Accra Center for National Culture hosts artisans and vendors with traditional Ghanaian goods. From textiles, to drums, to woodworks you can find it all here. It is located in Accra Central down the road from Black Star Square.

experience_reviews.content: Sharifah seemed to know every nook and cranny of the market. I wouldn't have discovered the spots she took us too on our own. Seeing the records felt like a different kind of history tour and the songs were such a vibe. Amazing piece of history.

result.name: Art Meets Fashion
result.description: Join our Accra insider for an inside look at galleries and boutiques in Accra. See why the city was recently named "Africa's Capital of Cool" by the New York Times while connecting with the people that make it happen.
result.title: Join a cultural curator for an art and design crawl through Accra
result.meetup: ANO Institute of Contemporary Arts, Accra
result.todo: 4 Boutique Visits, 4 Gallery Visits, 1 Curator Talk, Rooftop Cocktails, Jacuzzi
result.meetup_description: ANO is an art institution located on Lokko Road in Osu. You will notice its red exterior and the art installation in the front.
result.tips: You'll want to bring cash on this tour as there are lots of opportunities to support local artists and designers.

result.name: Batik Making Workshop
result.description: Grace Adovar has been practicing the Batik tradition of textile making for more than 30 years. She's served presidents and celebrities and is a celebrate female entrepreneur in Ghana. Join Grace and her team for a two hour workshop on batik fabric making where you'll learn the tradition and have the chance to make your very own fabric to take home.
result.title: Learn the traditional art of Batik, a form of textile dying found in Ghana, Indonesia, and Nigeria but called by different names.
result.todo: Batik Making Workshop, Light Breakfast
result.meetup_description: You'll meet at Gracia Fabrics, a textile and clothing shop owned by your host "Auntie Grace"
result.what_to_bring: Clothes that you don't mind getting dye on
result.tips: You'll be near dyes and hot wax on this experience, keep this in mind when choosing what to wear

experience_reviews.content:
We had a great experience at the Batik Making Workshop.  Ms. Grace's assistant Felicia supervised our experience.  She was kind and very accommodating.  In addition to myself, my husband (who is in a wheelchair), and my two younger daughters (9 and 5 YO) also participated. She was great and helped us all work through the process and create beautiful batiks. I highly recommend this experience for families and differently-abled people.  

Additionally, Ms. Grace has a shop full of beautiful clothes; and will do custom clothing.  She made a peplum shirt and jumpsuit for my daughters in two days.  I happily left with a suitcase full of beautiful clothes from her shop.

Really enjoyed this experience. We came here to learn about Batik making and ended up learning about history and way of life in Ghana. Ms Grace / team really welcomed us and spent a few hours after just talking to us. We really appreciated it.
Definitely doing this again when I go back to Ghana 12/19.  Grace and her team was so nice!  I was so impressed with the process and detail in takes to make a Batik.

This was a fantastic experience. First off, Grace has an amazing shop filled with gorgeous clothes and fabrics. Secondly, the workshop in back is an ideal spot to learn her craft. Felicia showed us how to make 2 different types of batik - block prints using wax and marbling. Our family had a wonderful time and we left with incredible memories and the fabrics we made.

My daughter and I participated in the Batik making workshop.
It was a great learning experience.

Learning and talking with Grace and Yaya was very insightful and an memory that my daughter and I will cherish.

This was an awesome, hands-on experience. Aunty Grace was thoughtful and informative. I loved that I got to walk away with batik that I made myself.  I recommend this experience to everybody and want to go back myself.

Worst customer service!
I purchased the Batik making workshop for 2. I arrive to the site (early) only to find that the curator Grace Andover was not around. Not only was she not around, but  as per her daughter, she had no plans on being on the premise for that day.  Grace's daughter subsequently offered to conduct the workshop as she was apologetic and stated no one from Tastemakers Africa reached out to them.  I would have been satisfied with the workshop being given by someone else, but i didn't receive another close to what i paid for.  Instead, I just watched  Grace's  daughter design some batik. I had no say in the design, nor did I engage with the activity in a hands-on manner. Once I arrived to my hotel I contacted Tastemakers Africa for a refund. No response at all. I ended up calling my bank and they refunded me my funds. Beware of this class; you may not get what you pay for

The experience was awesome. I went with my cousins and our children. Aunty Yaa Yaa was the main instructor and made sure the process went smoothly. I wasn't sure what to expect but once our fabrics went through their final rinses we were all pleasantly surprised to see how beautiful our creations came out. The only thing that was not accurate was the workshop is advertised to come with a light breakfast. There was nothing offered to drink nor eat. When I asked about it, no one knew what I was referring to. Aside from that this was an excellent experience and when I posted pictures online, many people asked me about it.
I enjoyed learning the batik making process and now I have one that I personally made. The class was a lot of fun!
I enjoyed learning the batik making process and now I have one that I personally made. The class was a lot of fun!
This experience was informative and fun! I walked away with two momentos that are unique to me and Ghana. My mom and friends enjoyed themselves making it an activity for all ages. Highly recommend!

result.name: Accra City Tour: Inside Edition
result.description: More than a city tour, see Accra through the lens of the man it's now synonymous with - the one and only Kwame Nkrumah. Discover why African leaders and Pan Africanists like Maya Angelou and WEB DuBois were drawn to this city, visit historic sites, and walk in his shoes.
result.title: An Accra City Tour with some extra swank on it.
result.todo: Historical Tour, Admission Fees, Local Snacks, Lunch
result.meetup_description: Independence Square is one of the most recognizable monuments in Accra and is located in Accra Central.

result.name: Mountain Biking in the Shai Hills
result.description: Stretch yourself and see some epic views at the Shai Hills Reserve. Just one hour north of Accra bordering the Akosombo road the hills offer one of the closest wildlife viewing areas to Accra and one of the most easily accessible in Ghana. You'll explore the reserve on a guided mountain bike tour and learn the art of abseiling.
result.title: Mountain Bike up the Shai Hills Reserve with an expert adventurist
result.todo: RT Transport, Hiking Guide, Mountain Bike, Breakfast, Lunch

result.name: Inside the Creative Process with A Producer And Collector
result.description: Spend the day with two of Accra's most creative thinkers who produce music videos for some of Ghana's hottest talent. Beyond the videos Afrodistrict regularly produces and creates art installations and "interactions" across the city. You'll get a behind the curtains look at their creative process and a chance to see what makes the city move under the surface.
result.title: Yayra is an art collector, filmmaker, stylist, and creative director, step into his world.
result.todo: Artist Talk, Light Snacks, Refreshments
result.meetup_description: Republic is centrally located in Osu on the side street of the Shoprite shopping center

result.name: Afro Fusion Cocktail Making
result.description: Eli is a mixologist specializing in using local ingredients to make masterfully crafted cocktails. You'll learn about sourcing, taste profiles, and spirit compatibility while making your very own concoction.
result.title: Better than happy hour, make your own cocktails with a popular mixologist
result.todo: Mixology Class, 3 Cocktails, Wine Tasting, Dinner
result.meetup_description: Located near coffeeshop road in Labone

result.name: Accra Through My Belly: Sunday Soups and Swallows
result.description: This experiences gets you to the heart of Accra through local food. From kelewele to red red to soups and fufu, your curator Frances - a well known foodie and event publicist in town, will take you to hidden places to find the best Ghanaian food and share her city's culinary traditions with you.
result.title: Learn where to find the best traditional food on a Sunday
result.todo: Two Food Tastings, One Meal, One Beer, One Soft Drink
result.meetup_description: Shoprite is a large grocery store on Oxford street in Osu

experience_reviews.content: Had a lovely lunch with Yayra!

result.name: Ghana Jollof From Start to Finish
result.description: Visit a local market where you will gather ingredients and see the hustle and bustle of daily life. Then go with the chef to his private residence where you will learn to make an Afro-fusion dish like a pro. Enjoy your labors and savor your meal.
result.title: Join a celebrity chef and make your own jollof.
result.meetup: A & C Mall, East Legon, Accra, Ghana
result.todo: Market Tour, Chef Led Cooking Class, Dinner, Wine Pairings
result.meetup_description: A&C Mall is the largest shopping center in the East Legon Neighborhood

experience_reviews.content: I had a wonderful time with Kwame!  I had to reschedule my experience and Yayra from TasteMakers worked behind the scenes to confirm Kwame's availability.  Kwame and I shopped at the mall as well as the local food markets for fresh ingredients.  We then went back to his lovely home where we cooked Ghanian Jollof Rice and Prawns, as well as talked about life in Ghana as well as in America. I would definitely do this experience again!!!!!

result.name: The Shrines of Jamestown
result.description: Visit 3 Gã shrines in the heart of the Gã community in Accra - Jamestown. Explore what these religious locations mean to the local neighborhood with someone who grew up there and participate in a libation
result.title: Explore Ga spiritual traditions with a 30 year resident
result.todo: Shrine Tour, Ga Spiritual Ceremony
result.meetup_description: Jamestown Boutique is a locally owned shop and center of community located in Accra's oldest neighborhood.
